column75: I am not offended by these pictures however, I fell that others who are more sensitive to the term "red skins" would feel attacked by people dressing up and coloring their skin to imitate native Americans.
column255: Show more controversial pictures to show and have a wider selection of feelings to choose from.

column75: The images of individuals appropriating Native American culture evoked a feeling of disappointment and mild frustration.  It's rather inappropriate yet openly accepted, and I'm sure Native Americans would feel similarly if not more intensely.
Seeing the photos made me happy because I do think that people should be able to dress the way that they want, the outfits also reminded me of people from back in the day
I was disgusted and frustrated knowing that there are people who continue to do this and/or do not understand why it is wrong.
They appeared to be very socially unacceptable, and racially unacceptable.
These people all look very white/Caucasian. That's basically the initial thought I had for most of them.
column255: For the policies regarding whether we should allow the use of Native American terms for branding/sports team names, I believe that we should ask the Native Americans themselves for their opinion so that's why I put neutral for those questions.

column75: I thought every picture where a person painted their face black in representation of African American culture is not okay. Whatever circumstance it may be, doing that is cultural appropriation
column255: nothing

column75: A lot of those pictures did not represent Native Americans correctly. There are a lot of stereotypes.

I don't understand what was going through peoples' minds to think it would be acceptable to paint your skin a different color as a costume. It is so disrespectful! The color of someone's skin is not a costume and is not something that should be taken as a joke.
culturally appropriating, offensive, dehumanizing, insensitive.
column255: Although I am less informed on the political and cultural issues that Native American/indigenous peoples face, as an Asian American I can emphasize with the racist caricatures that portray them as well as appropriation of their cultural garments/fashion.

column75: It was somewhat difficult to tell if some of the people in pictures were in blackface or actually African American. Blackface is pretty disturbing, definitely not something that should be considered okay by any means.
The people that just dressed up as native Americans or had battle paint would be okay but the other people with the extreme face paint went to the extreme

In a few of the photos I could not tell if the person was black or white therefore I was unaware of whether or not this was a racial slur. However I was disturbed by it when it was an instance of black face but for the other pictures I did not see much of an issue of people wearing wigs and such.

The images appear photoshopped and most of the people in the images do not seem very happy. For the images with afros, the first thing I noticed was the hair; it was harder to focus on what they were wearing.
I was slightly annoyed by how insensitive the sports fans were being by dressing the way they did, but they probably were not trying to offend anyone.
column255: I think this study is important, and I didn't realize how little Native Americans are thought of until doing this study.

column75: Mostly people supporting sports teams that don't truly have poor views of native americans, theyre just getting into the spirit of the game/team
column255: NA

column75: I find these images to be extremely disrespectful and disturbing. It is very inappropriate for white people to dress as black people for "fun" because it comes across as offensive and extremely inconsiderate of the struggles that black people have had to go through. I was uncomfortable with these images, especially the ones with painted faces.
column255: I have grown up in a very liberal town. The overwhelming majority of people in my town are white, but we had some kids from Boston attend my high school, and they were the only black people.

column75: I thought that the pictures of people dressed in black face were really bad, and I also saw some of the other pictures as halloween type costumes

The first couple of pictures shown were just random people dressed up like Native Americans. I didn't really know what to think because I had no clue what the situation of it was, or the purpose. However, towards the end, it was a lot of photos representing professional sports teams, where those dressing up are just showing spirit for their team. /

I think the images were extremely demeaning towards Native Americans. I was surprised by how today in the world people continue to dress like this to support a sports team. The most disturbing images were of people with their faces painted. While the Halloween costumes were to a lesser extent, they still show cultural appropriation which should never be tolerated.
I wondered if one could potentially be blackface but I wasn't sure, and I completely didn't realize the others were examples of it.
The people are dressing up as their team mascot, which is a native american figure. Some of the people put on red paint which is very racist and offensive.
column255: None

column75: Blackface is terrible and I cannot believe that these people thought it would be acceptable to be out in public dressed like this.
column255: On the first picture, I meant to answer "strongly disagree" for "is it acceptable for this person to be dressed like this". I misread the question and didn't realize until the next page. Thank you!

column75: I found that all of the outfits were unusual and typically not seen in public. /

These images reminded me of a discussion I had with my family fairly recently about the racist undertones (or just blatant racism in some cases) that come along with the Redskins and the Indians franchises and the tradition of the Cowboys playing the Redskins each thanksgiving. We agreed that it questionable at best that this game is considered tradition.
I feel like some of the images shown were totally ok and not in any way offensive, but the ones with red face paint is very unacceptable.

The blackface images shock me. The subsequent images shock me less, but the previous images make them worse in my mind due to context. Not worse than the blackface but worse than how I would have felt about them out of context.
column255: My family's main heritage is Serbian. I am not sure if that's of any concern.

column75: Having blackface on makes something so much worse than not having it on
column255: N/A

column75: As I kid, I would not have thought anything of these pictures, but now that I am culturally aware of the disrespect that these images show, I am disgusted with the idea that people think this is ok, not to mention privileged white adults.
I was offended at all the use of black face. When I saw white people wearing afros and chains it just looked goofy, not offensive to me, but goofy.

Regarding Blackface - The connotation here is that a person is trying to dress as a black person. What I have trouble distinguishing is the difference between the design of 'war paint' chosen, and the designation of 'redface' /  / Regarding the man with the long black wig - it was hard to determine if he was wearing makeup, as his skin tone was quite tan. If he was, I would mark that as blackface, and say that his effort to conform to the costume was minimal enough to be offensive.  /  / In general, I am more lenient towards public reactions to the costume in a sports context, because of the atmosphere established by the sport - a competition or (or war in the case of football) between two groups. I feel it to be more acceptable because it is likely others are dressed the same way.  /  / Generally, my feelings regarding the disparagement of Native Americans is tied inversely to the effort of the costume - greater effort to match the mascot leads to less disparagement. Conversely, if the costume is terribly executed to the point where you cant say the individual is dressed up as a native American, I was more lenient in that scenario.  /  / In regards to the halloween costumes, they were all pretty rough. Most of them showed native Americans in a neutral light, and one of them appeared to be a recreation costume for historical acting, being made out of seemingly real hide. The low effort headdress was something I feel to be offensive.
column255: One of my close friends in highschool (in Iowa) was a Native American from South Dakota. We never spoke much about what exactly it meant to him personally, although he was proud of his heritage, sporting a long hair braid. As to what extent his culture affected him personally, I do not know.  His family appeared to be a mixture of wealthy and poor, in the sense that they were able to afford 3 nice cars, but lived in a double trailer in an area with comparably cheap housing. The father was an ex soldier, but I do not know what he necessarily did for a living when he lived here.  /  / He did go to college, but I have not heard from him since. Apparently, he had issues with school, possibly related to who he associated with once he left our town.

column75: I don't necessarily agree with people dressing like that but there is something called free will.
I was shocked that anyone would actually think it is ok to dress like that (the pictures that involved black facing).
Depending on the situation I would say that is more or less accepted. However, I do understand how people can take offence by all of them
I was shocked and it seemed like cultural appropriation to me.

I have always been taught that dressing up as another culture, whether it be for sporting events or halloween or music festivals, is wrong and offensive. I find it especially disgusting when these cultures are sexualized (most commonly seen in women's halloween costumes and music festival outfits), as marginalized groups like native americans already face higher rates of sexual assault and abuse. People appropriating their culture only worsens this problem. Although I didn't mark the 2 or 3 pictures with only partial face paint as blackface in the survey, I still find them equally as offensive, I just was unsure if the term blackface also qualifies for tribal markings etc.
column255: My answers may skew research a bit because I grew up in a place where native issues are frequently talked about, both in local news and school curriculum (Alaska studies was a required class in high school and we had lots of Southeast Alaska Native programming through elementary and middle school). We were taught phrases in Haida, Tlingit, and Tsimshian throughout school, were shown performances of traditional dances and songs, and taken to totem pole exhibits to learn more about the history of the stories in each pole and how they are carved. A Native American art class was also offered for us in middle school. Although I had all this wonderful exposure throughout my childhood, I understand that kids growing up in most other areas do not get to experience this.

column255: The question regarding whether I though African Americans were more likely than whites to be sent to prison is too complicated to be limited to the responses given. column75: I think for the most part the sports ones were OK because in the case of the baseball team they are dressing as the mascot, not necessarily an actual Native American. With the football team, the Redskins, I felt like the only unacceptable one was the guy who looked like he purposefully put on a bunch of tanning oil or something. The others where they were literally painted red were not  racist in any way because that is the football team's color. It would be no different than fans painting themselves blue. Another good example is a team like the Raiders which are black and white. It is ok for people to paint themselves in black and white in this case. That is not be considered blackface or "whiteface", and obviously there has not been any outrage over face paint at Raider's games because of this.  /  / I do agree that maybe the team names could be changed, especially in the case of the Redskins. Changing both names to something like "The Natives" would be less offensive. I do not think many of the pictures reflect badly on actual Native Americans either. My grandma was Native American and she could not care less, but that is only one example. I also think that people dressing up as a "stereotypical native" that is represented in media is not harmful to the image of Native Americans. In the case of dressing up for a game, I do not think dressing up as a stereotypical Native American is any worse than dressing up as a stereotypical Viking in the case of the Minnesota Vikings, or dressing as a cowboy for the Dallas Cowboys, or dressing as a patriot for the New England Patriots. As a Texan myself I don't think people dressing as stereotypical "Cowboys from Texas" is offensive, and as someone with close family who is Native American, I do not think putting feathers in your hair or wearing face paint/paint made to look like war paint is offensive, and neither did my grandma.
column255: Some of the questions with the slider were hard to answer because I do not have enough knowledge to give an accurate value for those questions. With some of the opportunity questions I was using the case of my grandma and my dad, however that is only one case and probably gives me bias. But in this instance, my dad grew up very poor with a very poor white father as well as very poor native mother. Additionally, both sides of his family were poor if you look further up in the lineage. I would say this is not because one sides was white while one side was native, but instead because of the area and which they lived and the opportunities available to them. I do not think race had any thing to do with it. In my dad's case, he was able to work himself out of the area and gain wealth because what I believe was hard work, not because he was half white.  / In terms of learning about Native American history, I did not only learn this around Thanksgiving time in elementary school, but throughout much of my Texas history and United States History courses in high school. In these classes and textbooks we learned about the cruelties and atrocities committed against Native Americans such as the Trail of Tears. Of course the Native Americans would fight back, whether it was against Americans or Spanish conquistadors. This history is unfortunate, however I strongly believe that the people of today should not be blamed for the actions of their ancestors. I do not think banning any team or organization from using any type of name based on some type of Native American culture or history should be allowed. It is an important part of history. The only ones that push the limits are names like "The Redskins" because that could be considered racist. However, names like "The Chiefs" in the case of Kansas City are completely fine. I can see why some of these names may not be politically correct nowadays, however I still do not think they are offensive or reflect badly on actual Native Americans. /  /

Although I am somewhat indifferent to the choice to dress up in traditional native American clothing as some sort of costume, I do believe that many far left-leaning people would disapprove and react negatively toward the decision. The decision to paint one's skin to reflect the color of another race/ethnicity of people, however, is unacceptable in a moral context and I think it should be frowned upon or discouraged by all people, although our rights to express ourselves in any way we choose (including in racially insensitive ways) should not be infringed upon.
column255: I believe that many leftists would label me as extremely conservative, or far-right conservatives  would label me as a leftist, as a cop-out, due to my adoption of and belief in some conservative ideals, particularly in economic beliefs and issues  such as government regulations, but I identify with many more classical liberal ideologies in the sense of everyone's right's to freely express themselves as they choose and anyone having the freedom to support or oppose their decision through free speech, and am effectively a political left-leaning-moderate.

column75: It interesting to see this because initially the ones in costume with animal print that have the afro images my first thought to those pictures went toward Halloween costumes of representing the 70s age with the hair and all that. Yet however when it got to the costumes that were more directed toward certain african american iconic people such as the Tupac one, then it was more discomforting because in a way i feel like the costume would've done and indicated what is was regardless wether the person colored their face or not. So in a way it felt that those individuals who did color their skin seemed to have been using that as comedic factor along with the costume which makes it come off offensive.

None are necessarily positive or accurate representations of the Native American population, emphasis on the red skin, most likely none of these people are dressed that way to purposely offend someone. They dress like that because its Halloween or to support their team, even if its an inappropriate team name, not realizing the negative consequences it has on an entire population
I was initially shocked by the black face images

column75: I feel that costume dressing (i.e. for a Halloween party) is not necessarily negative towards Native Americans, unless the behavior of the person is mocking. However, putting on "an instance" of blackface is not acceptable, especially as the only likely ties towards dressing up as a Native American (in the given pictures) are to their sport.
It seems wrong to take dressing up as far as to paint their skin red. This to me creates a negative and sad stigma. I think however dressing up in a traditional/respectful way is okay.

column75: In the beginning I did not realize that the pictures were "blackface", but as soon as I did, I thought that the people who attempted to this act were reckless and maybe racists.

I know that this is an ongoing controversial issue here in the US, and seeing images of these fans going the extra mile to support they team brought me to think of what may be wrong with this. I do not think that the fans or people dressed in costumes mean anything negative towards the Native American culture and are simply just supporting their respective organizations. Although, a member of the Native American community could easily see this as being offensive. Depends on the perspective of the viewer.

I think it is acceptable for people to dress and style their hair however they want, but going so far as to perform blackface is a mockery of African-Americans and reflects poorly on the person performing it.

In my opinion the intention behind the way of dressing, in the images, was mostly to represent the Native American culture. Meaning that, people were dressed like that to imitate the culture, rather actually living the culture.

column75: I was unaware that some of the photos were of blackface, and once I realized that they were I wish I could go back and change some of my responses. Each photo I was shown made me upset because I think it is incredibly disrespectful and racist.

I have highly taken back that there are still teams with the name Redskins and people get excited dressing up like that. I also didn't like that all the models for the Native American Halloween costumes were obviously Caucasian.
column255: I think it's important to raise awareness that some people think it's okay to use nicknames such as "Redskins" and to stereotypically dress up as Native Americans. And I really hope Columbus Day one day the truth about Columbus is taught in grade/middle school because if it wasn't for my AP US History class in high school, I would not have known the extent of his horrific crimes and the ways he disrespected Native American and yet most people think he's some kind of hero... HELLO he wasn't even the first guy to find America so what's the big deal?!

column75: It took me a couple photos, but then I realized it was blackface and that's fucked up

The images are disgusting. It's scary to think about how many people don't see an issue with dressing like this and blatantly belittling black culture and black people. I think many white Americans never grasp the gravity of America's many crimes against people of color.
they were all offensive and there was many instances of blackface that were shocking

I feel in shock a bit to see modern pictures of people dressing in black face. I really only thought they did that in segregated and oppressive eras. It makes me feel sick to see that people still think that they can do this.

column75: It is extremely inappropriate for white people to treat African-American culture as a costume to put on as they please. I found it very offensive.

The images were a variety of Native American costumes ranging from situationally respectful to cartoonish and completely disrespectful. I think for the most part, and especially for the sports fans, they should not have dressed up that way, although the sports fans are probably mostly shielded from peer backlash because they are in a crowd of people doing the same thing. The red face was particularly bad, although in one case it was potentially just team-colored make-up as many fans from different team do (which so long as it is clearly not meant as a Native American disguise is fine).
